<subSubSection box="[151,408,223,249]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,408,223,249]" box="[151,408,223,249]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,408,223,249]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" reason="4">
<taxonomicName authority="White, 1862" authorityName="White" authorityYear="1862" box="[151,408,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,408,223,249]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,250,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="White, A." box="[257,408,223,249]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="175 - 284" refId="ref43428" refString="White, A. (1862) Class V - Insects (Insecta). Richardson's Museum of Natural History. 2, 175 - 284." type="journal article" year="1862">White, 1862</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,295,645]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,295,321]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
White with black spots, which vary in intensity and number among the different species (
<figureCitation box="[1298,1432,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-22@7.[151,1436,181,1772]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Characters used for the phylogeny (mainly head and pronotum): A, B. Habitus: Dysonia holgeri holgeri Cadena-Castañeda, 2011, male and female respectively. C, D. Head and pronotum in lateral view: C. Anaulacomera alexanderi Cadena-Castañeda, 2012. D. Anaphidna gracielae (Cadena-Castañeda, 2012). E–M. Head in frontal and lateral view: E, J. Markia hystrix (Westwood, 1844). F, L. Dissonulichen simplicipes simplicipes (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878). G. Quiva (Paraquiva) angieae Cadena-Castañeda, 2013. H. Aegimia maculifolia Dias, Rafael &amp; Naskrecki, 2012. I. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838). N. Paraphidnia gallina Giglio-Tos, 1898." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs. 2A–B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,204,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">33A</figureCitation>
). Antennae nodose, development of nodes variable (
<figureCitation box="[779,868,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-22@7.[151,1436,181,1772]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Characters used for the phylogeny (mainly head and pronotum): A, B. Habitus: Dysonia holgeri holgeri Cadena-Castañeda, 2011, male and female respectively. C, D. Head and pronotum in lateral view: C. Anaulacomera alexanderi Cadena-Castañeda, 2012. D. Anaphidna gracielae (Cadena-Castañeda, 2012). E–M. Head in frontal and lateral view: E, J. Markia hystrix (Westwood, 1844). F, L. Dissonulichen simplicipes simplicipes (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878). G. Quiva (Paraquiva) angieae Cadena-Castañeda, 2013. H. Aegimia maculifolia Dias, Rafael &amp; Naskrecki, 2012. I. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838). N. Paraphidnia gallina Giglio-Tos, 1898." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
); vertex conical and elevated moderately (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1424,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-22@7.[151,1436,181,1772]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Characters used for the phylogeny (mainly head and pronotum): A, B. Habitus: Dysonia holgeri holgeri Cadena-Castañeda, 2011, male and female respectively. C, D. Head and pronotum in lateral view: C. Anaulacomera alexanderi Cadena-Castañeda, 2012. D. Anaphidna gracielae (Cadena-Castañeda, 2012). E–M. Head in frontal and lateral view: E, J. Markia hystrix (Westwood, 1844). F, L. Dissonulichen simplicipes simplicipes (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878). G. Quiva (Paraquiva) angieae Cadena-Castañeda, 2013. H. Aegimia maculifolia Dias, Rafael &amp; Naskrecki, 2012. I. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838). N. Paraphidnia gallina Giglio-Tos, 1898." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 2K</figureCitation>
). Pronotum smooth and slightly expanded laterally (
<figureCitation box="[735,828,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1763,1787]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Characters used for the phylogeny (mainly head and thorax): A, B. Supra and infraocular evaginations: A. Paraphidnia gallina Giglio-Tos, 1898. B. Lichenomorphus montealegrezi Cadena-Castañeda, 2011. C–H. Head and pronotum: C. Dissonulichen simplicipes simplicipes (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878). D. Dysonia alipes (Westwood, 1844). E. Lichenodentix dentatithorax (Piza, 1951). F. Apolinaria hygracantha (Karsch, 1896). G. Markia hystrix (Westwood, 1844). H. Lichenodraculus matti Braun, 2011. I, J. Sternum: I. L. montealegrezi J. Machimoides sofiae Cadena-Castañeda, 2013. K. Denticles of the crest: Anaphidna gracielae (Cadena-Castañeda, 2012)." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
). Mesosternum rectangular (wider than long), lateral lobes slightly expanded. Main spine of hind femur conspicuous, lamellar, with serrate outer edge; other smaller spines fused into a plate (
<figureCitation box="[444,533,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1729,1753]" captionTargetBox="[151,1427,182,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-22@9.[151,1436,181,1705]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 4. Characters used for the phylogeny (habitus): A. Anaphidna gracielae (Cadena-Castañeda, 2012). B. Lichenomorphus montealegrezi Cadena-Castañeda, 2011. C. Markia hystrix (Westwood, 1844). D. Dissonulichen simplicipes simplicipes (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878). E. Dysonia alipes (Westwood, 1844)." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
). Male cerci variable in shape, conical (
<figureCitation box="[990,1136,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 33K, M</figureCitation>
), triangular, branches flattened (
<figureCitation box="[227,328,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 33G</figureCitation>
) or pointed and thin (
<figureCitation box="[569,671,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 33C</figureCitation>
). Male subgenital plate shorter than length of cerci (
<figureCitation box="[1253,1424,475,502]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs. 33H, J, L</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor curved and broadened, with robust valves (
<figureCitation box="[760,859,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-22@7.[151,1436,181,1772]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Characters used for the phylogeny (mainly head and pronotum): A, B. Habitus: Dysonia holgeri holgeri Cadena-Castañeda, 2011, male and female respectively. C, D. Head and pronotum in lateral view: C. Anaulacomera alexanderi Cadena-Castañeda, 2012. D. Anaphidna gracielae (Cadena-Castañeda, 2012). E–M. Head in frontal and lateral view: E, J. Markia hystrix (Westwood, 1844). F, L. Dissonulichen simplicipes simplicipes (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878). G. Quiva (Paraquiva) angieae Cadena-Castañeda, 2013. H. Aegimia maculifolia Dias, Rafael &amp; Naskrecki, 2012. I. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838). N. Paraphidnia gallina Giglio-Tos, 1898." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs. 2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[871,907,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1729,1753]" captionTargetBox="[151,1427,182,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-22@9.[151,1436,181,1705]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 4. Characters used for the phylogeny (habitus): A. Anaphidna gracielae (Cadena-Castañeda, 2012). B. Lichenomorphus montealegrezi Cadena-Castañeda, 2011. C. Markia hystrix (Westwood, 1844). D. Dissonulichen simplicipes simplicipes (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878). E. Dysonia alipes (Westwood, 1844)." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">4E</figureCitation>
). Males larger than females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1064,547,573]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,295,645]" box="[199,1064,547,573]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,547,573]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,547,573]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Type</typeStatus>
species.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1844" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1844" box="[361,787,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Phaneroptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alipes">
<emphasis box="[361,590,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Phaneroptera alipes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Westwood, J. O." box="[597,787,547,573]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="87 - 88" refId="ref43382" refString="Westwood, J. O. (1844) Illustrations of two new species of grasshoppers from Colombia and Mexico. Arcana Entomologica or Illustrations of New, Rare and Interesting Insects, 2 (18), 87 - 88, pl. 70." type="journal article" year="1844">Westwood, 1844</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,295,645]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,583,609]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Distribution.</emphasis>
Mainly in medium elevations of the Andes from 
<collectingCountry box="[915,1025,583,609]" name="Colombia" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Colombia</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[1064,1149,583,609]" name="Bolivia" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, with members in central and southern 
<collectingCountry box="[302,370,619,645]" name="Brazil" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Map 16).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,624,1371,1395]" box="[151,624,1371,1395]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,240,1371,1395]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Map 16.</emphasis>
Distribution map of 
<taxonomicName box="[452,624,1371,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[452,536,1372,1395]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,1441,2044]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1441,1467]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Bruner, 1915" authorityName=", Bruner" authorityYear="1915" box="[342,711,1441,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamellipes">
<emphasis box="[342,558,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia lamellipes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bruner, L." box="[565,711,1441,1468]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="284 - 404" refId="ref38464" refString="Bruner, L. (1915) Notes on tropical American Tettigonoidea (Locustodea). Annals of the Carnegie Museum, 9 (3 - 4), 284 - 404." type="journal article" year="1915">Bruner, 1915</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is considered a 
<emphasis box="[892,1057,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">nomen dubium</emphasis>
. The original description is based on an immature female, which impedes the comparison with other species, and the whereabouts of the 
<typeStatus box="[1313,1361,1478,1504]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">type</typeStatus>
specimen are unknown. Preceding the description of 
<taxonomicName authority=", Bruner (1915)" authorityName=", Bruner" authorityYear="1915" box="[708,1040,1513,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamellipes">
<emphasis box="[708,861,1513,1539]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">D. lamellipes</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Bruner, L." box="[878,1040,1513,1540]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="284 - 404" refId="ref38464" refString="Bruner, L. (1915) Notes on tropical American Tettigonoidea (Locustodea). Annals of the Carnegie Museum, 9 (3 - 4), 284 - 404." type="journal article" year="1915">Bruner (1915)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
mentions that in the same area in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,233,1549,1575]" name="Bolivia" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
was collected a female probably belonging to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[785,1016,1549,1575]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctifrons">
<emphasis box="[785,1016,1549,1575]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia punctifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(now 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[1095,1420,1549,1575]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lichenomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctifrons">
<emphasis box="[1095,1420,1549,1575]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Lichenomorphus punctifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Perhaps the 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Bruner" authorityYear="1915" box="[288,437,1585,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamellipes">
<emphasis box="[288,437,1585,1611]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">D. lamellipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nymph belongs to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[652,809,1585,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lichenomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctifrons">
<emphasis box="[652,809,1585,1611]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">L. punctifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
too.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,1441,2044]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Costa Lima, A. M. &amp; Guitton, N." box="[361,689,1621,1647]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="399 - 418" refId="ref40274" refString="Costa Lima, A. M. &amp; Guitton, N. (1960) Genero Dysonia (Orth. Tettig. Phaneropteridae) Parte I. Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciencias, 32, 399 - 418." type="journal article" year="1960">Costa Lima &amp; Guitton (1960)</bibRefCitation>
described specimens from the same province in 
<collectingCountry box="[1225,1307,1621,1647]" name="Bolivia" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
as males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Bruner" authorityYear="1915" box="[151,301,1657,1683]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamellipes">
<emphasis box="[151,301,1657,1683]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">D. lamellipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on the shared locality. However, it is common to find species of the different genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1862" box="[1336,1429,1658,1683]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1336,1429,1658,1683]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[151,346,1693,1719]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2011" box="[151,342,1693,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lichenomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lichenomorphus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Braun &amp; García" authorityYear="2022" box="[402,562,1693,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Dissonulichen" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[402,562,1693,1719]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dissonulichen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurring in the same area (with all the species previously treated as belonging to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1862" box="[224,317,1730,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[224,317,1730,1755]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). According to the drawing of male terminalia in Costa Lima &amp; Guiton (1961) cerci and subgenital plate are fairly similar to the ones of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2011" box="[570,752,1765,1791]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holgeri">
<emphasis box="[570,752,1765,1791]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia holgeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Without the 
<typeStatus box="[906,954,1766,1792]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">type</typeStatus>
specimen it is impossible to determine the generic identity of Bruner’s species. It could even belong to some other genus whose nymphs share similar color patterns. This happened with 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker, 1871" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1871" box="[481,825,1837,1863]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Valna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigropicta">
<emphasis box="[481,668,1837,1863]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Valna nigropicta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Walker, F." box="[674,825,1837,1863]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref43354" refString="Walker, F. (1871) Catalogue of the Specimens of Dermaptera Saltatoria in the Collection of the British Museum, Supplement, 1 - 116." type="book chapter" year="1871">Walker, 1871</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, described from a whitish immature female with black markings, that 
<bibRefCitation author="Kirby, W. F." box="[318,465,1873,1899]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="1 - 562" refId="ref41426" refString="Kirby, W. F. (1906) Orthoptera Saltatoria. Part I. (Achetidae et Phasgonuridae). A Synonymic Catalogue of Orthoptera (Orthoptera Saltatoria, Locustidae vel Acridiidae), 2, i - viii + 1 - 562." type="journal article" year="1906">Kirby (1906)</bibRefCitation>
included with some doubt in genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1862" box="[871,964,1874,1899]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[871,964,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Eventually it was found to be a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[183,612,1909,1936]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthodis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aquilina">
<emphasis box="[183,410,1909,1935]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Acanthodis aquilina</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1758)
</taxonomicName>
, thereby belonging to subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[987,1172,1909,1935]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Pseudophyllinae">Pseudophyllinae</taxonomicName>
(Costa Lima &amp; Guiton 1960, based on a communication by D.R. Ragge).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,1441,2044]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Costa Lima &amp; Guitton" authorityYear="1960" box="[199,415,1981,2007]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bridarollii">
<emphasis box="[199,415,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Dysonia bridarollii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<materialsCitation location="Costa Lima" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Costa Lima" typeStatus="holotype">
<collectingRegion box="[421,550,1981,2007]" isEnumeration="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<collectingRegion box="[421,485,1981,2007]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Costa</collectingRegion>
<collectingRegion box="[491,550,1981,2007]" country="Peru" name="Lima" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Lima</collectingRegion>
</collectingRegion>
&amp; Guiton, 1960 is only known from a female. The 
<typeStatus box="[1119,1217,1981,2007]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">holotype</typeStatus>
could not be examined and the status of this species is uncertain, which is why it is not included in the key to species
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="key">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,465,151,177]" box="[151,465,151,177]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,465,151,177]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
Key to species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1862" box="[366,465,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[366,465,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Dysonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<key pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyStep pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" box="[151,1436,220,242]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,220,242]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">1. Inner branch of male cerci variable in shape, but never pointed or needle-shaped and not exceeding the outer branch....... 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
- Inner branch of male cerci elongated, pointed, and needle-shaped, exceeding the length of the outer branch (
<figureCitation box="[1264,1353,249,271]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33C</figureCitation>
)............................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castaneda 2011" authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2011" box="[1099,1436,278,301]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holgeri">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1099,1199,278,300]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">D. holgeri</emphasis>
Cadena-Castañeda 2011
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" box="[151,1436,308,330]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,308,330]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
2. Medium-sized (
<quantity box="[377,485,308,330]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.75" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="37.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="35.0">35–40 mm</quantity>
), male subgenital plate with articulated styli.......................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" box="[151,1436,337,359]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,337,359]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
- Small (
<quantity box="[295,367,338,359]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="29.0">29 mm</quantity>
), male subgenital plate without articulated styli (
<figureCitation box="[834,924,337,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33D</figureCitation>
)........... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Costa Lima &amp; Guitton" authorityYear="1960" box="[1066,1155,337,359]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zikani">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1066,1155,337,359]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">D. zikani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Costa Lima, A. M. &amp; Guitton, N." box="[1161,1436,337,359]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" pagination="399 - 418" refId="ref40274" refString="Costa Lima, A. M. &amp; Guitton, N. (1960) Genero Dysonia (Orth. Tettig. Phaneropteridae) Parte I. Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciencias, 32, 399 - 418." type="journal article" year="1960">
<collectingRegion box="[1161,1273,337,359]" isEnumeration="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<collectingRegion box="[1161,1216,338,359]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Costa</collectingRegion>
<collectingRegion box="[1222,1273,337,359]" country="Peru" name="Lima" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Lima</collectingRegion>
</collectingRegion>
&amp; Guitton, 1960
</bibRefCitation>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" box="[151,1436,367,389]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,367,389]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">3. Body with scarce black markings; male cerci with conical branches, similar in size or with a longer outer branch......... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
- Body more extensively marked black; male cerci with flattened and triangular branches, outer branch with a notch in the anteroapical portion of the ventral margin (
<figureCitation box="[579,668,425,447]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33G</figureCitation>
)........................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Gorochov, 2012" authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2012" box="[1166,1436,425,447]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pardalis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1166,1276,425,447]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">D. pardalis</emphasis>
Gorochov, 2012
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" box="[151,1436,455,477]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,455,477]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">4. Branches of male cerci conical, and similar in size and shape................................................... 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
- Apex of outer branch of male cerci obtuse, with some denticulations on margin in dorsal view; inner branch subtriangular with truncate apex (
<figureCitation box="[368,445,513,535]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33I</figureCitation>
).............................................. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Costa Lima &amp; Guitton" authorityYear="1960" box="[1027,1155,513,535]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monticola">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1027,1155,513,535]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">D. monticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Costa Lima, A. M. &amp; Guitton, N." box="[1161,1436,513,535]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" pagination="399 - 418" refId="ref40274" refString="Costa Lima, A. M. &amp; Guitton, N. (1960) Genero Dysonia (Orth. Tettig. Phaneropteridae) Parte I. Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciencias, 32, 399 - 418." type="journal article" year="1960">
<collectingRegion box="[1161,1273,513,535]" isEnumeration="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<collectingRegion box="[1161,1216,514,535]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Costa</collectingRegion>
<collectingRegion box="[1222,1273,513,535]" country="Peru" name="Lima" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Lima</collectingRegion>
</collectingRegion>
&amp; Guitton, 1960
</bibRefCitation>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
5. Outer branch of male cerci twice as long as inner branch, sub-triangular and slightly curved inward from the middle to the apex; inner branch triangular and sclerotized (
<figureCitation box="[607,697,572,594]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33K</figureCitation>
); styli of subgenital plate cylindrical and slightly curved inward in the middle (
<figureCitation box="[233,315,601,623]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33J</figureCitation>
)..................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Walker, 1869)" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[1156,1436,601,623]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dysonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melaleuca">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1156,1286,601,623]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">D. melaleuca</emphasis>
(Walker, 1869)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,220,682]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<keyLead pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
- Outer branch of male cerci almost as long as inner branch (
<figureCitation box="[812,907,631,653]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33M</figureCitation>
); styli of subgenital plate reduced and triangular (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,491,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-437@57.[164,1424,491,1910]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 33. Dysonia species. A–C. D. holgeri. D–E. D. zikani. F–G. D. pardalis. H–I. D. monticola. J–K. D. melaleuca. L–M. D. alipes. A. Habitus in lateral view. B, D, F, H, J, L. Subgenital plates. C, E, G, I, K, M. Cerci. (Figs. D–E., H–J. after Costa-Lima &amp; Guitton, 1960)." pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33L</figureCitation>
)......................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Westwood, 1844)" baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[1167,1436,660,682]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Phaneroptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alipes">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1167,1253,660,682]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">D. alipes</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Westwood, J. O." box="[1266,1429,660,682]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" pagination="87 - 88" refId="ref43382" refString="Westwood, J. O. (1844) Illustrations of two new species of grasshoppers from Colombia and Mexico. Arcana Entomologica or Illustrations of New, Rare and Interesting Insects, 2 (18), 87 - 88, pl. 70." type="journal article" year="1844">Westwood, 1844</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,709,1768,1792]" box="[151,709,1768,1792]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,240,1768,1792]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Map 17.</emphasis>
Distribution map of 
<taxonomicName box="[452,709,1768,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lichenomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[452,622,1768,1792]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Lichenomorphus</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
